03728nmm a2200493Ia 9780814763520DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20201998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147635207 a10.18574/nyu/9780814763520.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547592  a(OCoLC)50745272  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a305.3109731 aKann, Mark E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Republic of Men :bThe American Founders, Gendered Language, and Patriarchal Politics /cMark E. Kann. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Culture of Manhood -- t2. The Grammar of Manhood -- t3. The Bachelor and Other Disorderly Men -- t4. The Family Man and Citizenship -- t5. The Better Sort and Leadership -- t6. The Heroic Man and National Destiny -- t7. The Founders' Gendered Legacy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aWhat role did manhood play in early American Politics? In A Republic of Men, Mark E. Kann argues that the American founders aspired to create a "republic of men" but feared that "disorderly men" threatened its birth, health, and longevity. Kann demonstrates how hegemonic norms of manhood-exemplified by "the Family Man," for instance--were deployed as a means of stigmatizing unworthy men, rewarding responsible men with citizenship, and empowering exceptional men with positions of leadership and authority, while excluding women from public life. Kann suggests that the founders committed themselves in theory to the democratic proposition that all men were created free and equal and could not be governed without their own consent, but that they in no way believed that "all men" could be trusted with equal liberty, equal citizenship, or equal authority. The founders developed a "grammar of manhood" to address some difficult questions about public order. Were America's disorderly men qualified for citizenship? Were they likely to recognize manly leaders, consent to their authority, and defer to their wisdom? A Republic of Men compellingly analyzes the ways in which the founders used a rhetoric of manhood to stabilize American politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814763520.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763520zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814763520/original  a978-3-11-071692-4 New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA